'''Rare Disease Day''' is an [[observance]] held on the last day of February<ref name=millions/><ref name=luce>{{cite web | last=Luce | first=Jim | publisher=[[The Huffington Post]] | accessdate=20 February 2009 | date=10 February 2009 | title="Rare Diseases" Increasingly Common, Not Rare for Afflicted | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jim-luce/rare-diseases-increasingl_b_165780.html}}</ref> to raise awareness for [[rare disease]]s and improve access to treatment and medical representation for individuals with rare diseases and their families.<ref name=millions/><ref name=about>{{cite web | url=http://www.rarediseaseday.org/article/why-rare-disease-day | accessdate=14 February 2009 | title=Why Rare Disease Day? | publisher=Rare Disease Day}}</ref><ref name=eurordis/><ref>{{cite web | publisher=[[United States National Library of Medicine]] | date=15 February 2009 | accessdate=17 February 2009 | title=Rare Disease Day 2009 | url=http://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/spotlight=rarediseaseday2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  It was established in 2008 because, according to the [[European Organization for Rare Diseases]] (EURORDIS), treatment for many rare diseases is insufficient, as are the social networks to support individuals with rare diseases and their families;<ref name=novartis/> furthermore, while there were already numerous days dedicated to sufferers of individual diseases (such as [[AIDS]], [[cancer]], etc.), there had previously not been a day for representing sufferers of rare diseases.<ref name=eurordis/> In 2009 Rare Disease Day went global as NORD ([[National Organization for Rare Disorders]]) mobilized 200 rare disease patient advocacy organizations in the United States while organizations in China, Australia, Taiwan, and Latin America also lead efforts in their respective countries to coordinate activities and promote the day.<ref name=about/>  In addition, leading rare disease patient advocacy organizations including the [[Global Genes Project]] have joined forces to promote Rare Disease Day.

==2008==
The first Rare Disease Day was held on 29 February 2008 in numerous [[Europe]]an nations and in [[Canada]] through the [[Canadian Organization for Rare Disorders]],<ref name=eurordis>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurordis.org/article.php3?id_article=1593 | title=29 February 2008: First European Rare Disease Day | publisher=European Organisation for Rare Diseases | date=December 2007 | accessdate=14 February 2009 | first=Jerome | last=Parisse-Brassens}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> organized by EURORDIS.<ref name=luce/><ref name=zurynski/><ref name=first>{{cite web | title=February 29th Is The First Rare Disease Day | url=http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/98767.php | date=28 February 2008 | accessdate=14 February 2009 | publisher=[[Medical News Today]]}}</ref><ref name=nord>{{cite web | url=http://rarediseaseday.us/about/history/ | title=History of Rare Disease Day | publisher=[[National Organization for Rare Disorders]]}}</ref> The date was chosen because February 29 is a "rare day,"<ref>Nevertheless, Rare Disease Day was intended to be an annual event, and would fall on February 28 in non-[[leap year]]s.  See {{cite web | url=http://www.eurordis.org/article.php3?id_article=1593 | title=29 February 2008: First European Rare Disease Day | publisher=European Organisation for Rare Diseases | date=December 2007 | accessdate=14 February 2009 | first=Jerome | last=Parisse-Brassens}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and 2008 was the 25th anniversary of the passing of the [[Orphan Drug Act]] in the [[United States]].<ref name=novartis>{{cite web | title=February 29 is Rare Disease Day in Europe | url=http://www.novartis.com/newsroom/news/2008-02-28_rare-disease-day.shtml | publisher=[[Novartis]] | accessdate=14 February 2009}}</ref>  Individuals observing Rare Disease Day took part in walks and press conferences to raise public awareness of rare diseases, organized fundraisers, and wrote en masse to government [[Representation (politics)|representatives]];<ref name=first/>  health-related [[non-profit organizations]] across numerous countries also held events, gatherings, and campaigns.<ref name=orpha>{{cite web | url=http://www.orpha.net/actor/EuropaNews/2008/080213.html | work=OrphaNews Europe | accessdate=15 February 2009 | date=13 February 2008 | title=The First European Rare Disease Day is only two weeks away...}}</ref>  The day also included an open session of the [[European Parliament]] specifically dedicated to discussing policy issues relating to rare diseases.<ref name=zurynski>{{cite journal | doi=10.1136/adc.2007.134940 | title=Rare childhood diseases: how should we respond? | volume=93 | issue=12 | journal=Archives of Disease in Childhood | year=2008 | pages=1071&ndash;1074 | author=Zurynski, Y; Frith, K; Leonard, H; Elliott, E | pmid=18684747}}</ref>  The days leading up to Rare Disease Day included other policy-related events in numerous locations, such as a reception in the [[British Parliament]] where policymakers met with individuals with rare diseases to discuss issues such as "equal access and availability of prevention, diagnosis, treatment and rehabilitation."<ref name=harris>{{cite web | url=http://www.evanharris.org.uk/news/000175/a_rare_day_for_rare_disease.html | title=A Rare Day for Rare Disease | date=29 February 2008 | publisher=[[Evan Harris]] | accessdate=15 February 2009}}</ref>

==2009==
Rare Disease Day was observed for the first time in [[Panama]], [[Colombia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]], the [[People's Republic of China]], and the [[United States]].<ref name=pharmi/>

In the [[United States]] NORD ([[National Organization for Rare Disorders]]) signed on to coordinate Rare Disease Day on February 28 and collaborated with media partner [[The Discovery Channel]] and program partner ''[[Mystery Diagnosis]]'',<ref name=medianewsline>{{cite web | url=http://www.medianewsline.com/news/133/ARTICLE/4004/2009-02-10.html | publisher=MediaNewsLine.com | accessdate=14 February 2009 | date=10 February 2009 | title=Discovery Health to air "Mystery Diagnosis ' on Rare Disease Day 2009}}</ref> as well about 180 other partners,<ref name=medianewsline/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rarediseaseday.us/rare_disease_day/rare_disease_day_partners | title=Rare Disease Day Partners! | accessdate=14 February 2009 | publisher=[[National Organization for Rare Disorders]]}}</ref> to organize activities across the country for the observance of Rare Disease Day.<ref name=millions>{{cite web | url=http://sev.prnewswire.com/health-care-hospitals/20090213/DC7071513022009-1.html | title=Millions Around World to Observe Rare Disease Day | accessdate=14 February 2009 | date=13 February 2009 | publisher=[[PR Newswire]]}}</ref><ref name=nord/><ref name=pharmi>{{cite web | url=http://www.pharmiweb.com/pressreleases/pressrel.asp?ROW_ID=5655 | title=February 28th is Rare Disease Day | date=12 February 2009 | accessdate=14 February 2009 | work=PharmiWeb.com}}</ref><ref name=mystery>{{cite web | url=http://sev.prnewswire.com/television/20090209/PH6815409022009-1.html | publisher=[[PR Newswire]] | accessdate=14 February 2009 | title=National Organization for Rare Disorders To Partner With Discovery Health and 'MYSTERY DIAGNOSIS' for Rare Disease Day 2009 | date=9 February 2009}}</ref><ref name=vhl>{{cite web | url=http://www.send2press.com/newswire/2009-02-0205-008.shtml | accessdate=14 February 2009 | last=Zander | first=Carly | title=VHL Family Alliance Announced Partner in Rare Disease Day  | date=5 February 2009}}</ref>  Several United States state governments issued proclamations regarding Rare Disease Day.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rarediseaseday.us/rare_disease_day/rare_disease_day_map | title=Current Rare Disease Day Proclamations! | publisher=[[National Organization for Rare Disorders]] | accessdate=14 February 2009}}</ref>

In Europe, over 600 patient advocacy and support organizations, again coordinated by EURORDIS, also planned events.<ref name=pharmi/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/news/Derby-mum-boy-rare-illness-visit-Westminster/article-686002-detail/article.html | title=Derby mum of boy with rare illness to visit Westminster | work=[[Derby Evening Telegraph]] | date=11 February 2009 | accessdate=16 February 2009}}</ref>

==2010==
Rare Disease Day 2010 was observed on Sunday February 28. The theme for Rare Disease Day 2010 was "Patients and Researchers: Partners for Life".

The event saw the participation of a total of 46 countries participated in 2010.<ref name="urlRare Disease Day 2010 | www.eurordis.org">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurordis.org/content/rare-disease-day-2010 |title=Rare Disease Day 2010 - www.eurordis.org |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref> Newcomers from Eastern Europe were Latvia, Lithuania Slovenia and Georgia. 3 African countries joined the event as well.

==2011==
Rare Disease Day 2011 took place on February 28. Theme for 2011 was "Rare Diseases and Health Inequalities", to focus on differences for rare disease patients between and within countries, and compared to other segments of society, in order to ensure equal access for patients to health care, social services and rights, and to orphan drugs and treatments. 

